{"title":"BiViT: Extremely Compressed Binary Vision Transformers","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Binarizing self-attention in Vision Transformers causes large errors because softmax attention scores are positive, highly sparse, and long-tailed; softmax-agnostic binarization (e.g., pre-softmax Bool/learned fixed thresholds) mismatches these dynamics and degrades accuracy.","method":"Introduce Softmax-aware Binarization (SAB): formulate per-row attention binarization as a sparse-coding/coordinate-descent problem to derive an optimal threshold T* and basis v that minimize quantization error, then approximate it efficiently at inference by predicting T ≈ β·max(a_s) via linear regression and discarding v to keep compute unchanged. Use STE to backpropagate gradients w.r.t. softmax outputs (not pre-softmax), making training softmax-aware. This reduces attention quantization error from 0.683 (BiBERT) to ~2.7e-05 and improves TinyImageNet accuracy when binarizing attention (e.g., NesT-T: 68.51%→70.73%)."},{"problem":"Directly binarizing all modules in ViTs destroys crucial pretrained information—especially in MLPs with many 1×1 layers—leading to severe performance drops and unstable optimization.","method":"Propose Cross-layer Binarization (CLB), a two-stage scheme that decouples modules to preserve pretrained information: first binarize all self-attention blocks (with SAB) while keeping MLPs full-precision; then binarize MLPs. This mitigates mutual interference between modules, accelerates convergence, and yields higher accuracy than one-step or traditional two-step (activations-then-weights) training (TinyImageNet/NesT-T with FP MLP activations: 69.83% vs 58.20% one-step and 65.64% traditional two-step)."},{"problem":"Binary ViTs have limited representational capacity; fixed per-channel scaling factors in weight binarization underutilize channel importance and hinder recovery of pretrained knowledge.","method":"Introduce Parameterized Weight Scales (PWS): replace conventional computed scales with learnable per-channel scale parameters trained end-to-end, enhancing representation without changing architecture or complexity. Applied to both attention and MLP modules, PWS yields consistent gains (e.g., TinyImageNet/NesT-T: +4.2% Top-1 when added to binarized attention; +1.3% when added to binarized MLPs)."}]}
